Layaway Goodies recognises revenues from layaway transactions (putting merchandise aside for customers who make partial payment) when the merchandise is placed on layaway. 
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1: Background
a.What do you think of Layaway Goodies’ revenue recognition policy? Does the company face any unique issues in the recognition of expenses?
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
Layaway Goodies should recognise revenue when the good is delivered (i.e., its benefits and risks are transferred to the buyer) and match expenses then. 
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
b.Should Layaway Goodies use a different revenue recognition method if the customer has made a firm commitment to buy the merchandise and Layaway Goodies does not have to refund any money to the customer if (s)he does not buy the product?Justify your answer.Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
No, the revenue recognition is the same regardless of whether payment is assured. The first criteria for revenue recognition is met (the benefit is measurable) but the second criterion is not met yet (revenue has not been earned). Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
OnlineDatabasesprovides customers with nonexclusive access to proprietary databases on its website for a non-refundable annual fee. The company provides customers an identification number and training in the use of databases; post-training, the company incurs no incremental costs to

15154508747921504.text:
the use of databases; post-training, the company incurs no incremental costs to provide services to its customers. Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-2: Background
a.Discuss when OnlineDatabasesshould recognise revenue, along with any unique issues that the company may face in the recognition of expenses.
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-2
Although (on completion of training) OnlineDatabasesincurs no incremental costs to provide service, no revenue should be recognized on completion of the initial setup because the economic substance of the contract calls for services to be delivered over time. Therefore, revenue should be recognized over the annual term of the contract as services are provided.  To achieve matching, OnlineDatabasesshould capitalize and amortize the costs of providing the services.  Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-2
Xerox often includes a service contract when it sells a copier (typically for one year). How do you think Xerox should recognize the revenue of this sale? 
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-3: Background
Xerox should split the price of the copier into two components. The portion of the price that relates to the service contract, should be recognized over the term of the contract. The portion that relates to the equipment should be recognized either at the time of sale or, if the equipment requires installation, when the equipment is delivered and installed. Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-3

BioDrugsLtd purchased a patent for a new drug for $150,000 on January 1st 2007. At the time of the purchase the patent was valid for 5 years. The company decided to use a straight line amortization method. On December 31st, 2007 the company learned that the drug is not as effective as other competitor drugs already on the market. BioDrugs, Ltd -Intangible assets QUESTION TWO
What should the company do when preparing the fiscal yearend financial statements on December 31st, 2007? Discuss the effects (if any) on the balance sheet and the income statement. BioDrugs, Ltd -Intangible assets QUESTION TWO
By the end of the first year the company should have amortized 30,000 (150,000 / 5) per year of the value of the patent. Therefore, the Income Statement is affected by a depreciation expense of 30,000 and the Balance Sheet will show a Net Book Value for the patent of 120,000.BioDrugs, Ltd -Intangible assets QUESTION TWO
Given the information learned at the end of the year, the company should consider impairing the asset. It is very possible that the patent will not produce the expected future benefits given the competitor drugs on the market. The size of the impairment should be estimated by the company –that is the total value lost in future benefits.BioDrugs, Ltd -Intangible assets QUESTION TWO
Other Notes:Assume that the company decides to write down part of the value of the asset (X). That means that the book value on the balance sheet will be 120,000 –X and the total income effect will be 30,000 (depreciation expense) + X (impairment loss).Alternatively, the company can actually write the asset off (i.e., X=120,000). In this case, the company expects no future benefits from the patent. BioDrugs, Ltd -Intangible assets QUESTION TWO

Layaway Goodies recognises revenues from layaway transactions (putting merchandise aside for customers who make partial payment) when the merchandise is placed on layaway. 
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1: Background
a.What do you think of Layaway Goodies’ revenue recognition policy? Does the company face any unique issues in the recognition of expenses?
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
Layaway Goodies should recognise revenue when the good is delivered (i.e., its benefits and risks are transferred to the buyer) and match expenses then. 
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
b.Should Layaway Goodies use a different revenue recognition method if the customer has made a firm commitment to buy the merchandise and Layaway Goodies does not have to refund any money to the customer if (s)he does not buy the product?Justify your answer.Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
No, the revenue recognition is the same regardless of whether payment is assured. The first criteria for revenue recognition is met (the benefit is measurable) but the second criterion is not met yet (revenue has not been earned). Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
OnlineDatabasesprovides customers with nonexclusive access to proprietary databases on its website for a non-refundable annual fee. The company provides customers an identification number and training in the use of databases; post-training, the company incurs no incremental costs to provide services to its customers. Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-2: Background
a.Discuss when OnlineDatabasesshould recognise revenue, along with any unique issues that the company may face in the recognition of expenses.
Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-2
Although (on completion of training) OnlineDatabasesincurs no incremental costs to provide service, no revenue should be recognized on completion of the initial setup because the economic substance of the contract calls for services to be delivered over time. Therefore, revenue should be recognized over the annual term of the contract as services are provided. Forbes: Stock Buybacks Made Corporations Vulnerable (April 24, 2020)Relevance watch 1

Instead of innovation, companies whose business models were undergoing a high degree of uncertainty and change repurchase stock.Since Q1 2009, S&P 500 companies have spent, cumulatively, $5.4 trillion on stock buybacks.Perhaps no greater example is the U.S. airlines, an industry that has collectively spent 96% of free cash flow on buybacks over the last decade, leaving virtually no cash cushion to prepare for a down cycle.Relevance watch 1
Despite what many CEOs consistently say on earnings calls—that buybacks “return value” to shareholders—share repurchases in actuality put a company and its shareholders in a much riskier position.“Instead of using capital to invest in the future (i.e. electric cars), car companies like GM buy back company stock.”So do stock buybacks increase risk for long-term shareholders?Relevance watch 1
Relevance watch 2
One of the most important metrics a firm is valuated by capital markets is EPS.EPS = Net income / # of shares outstandingDo firms reduce number of shares outstanding by repurchasing their own shares and thereby increase EPS? Relevance watch 2
Relevance watch 2 
We investigate whether firms use stock repurchases to meet or beat analysts’ earnings per share (EPS) forecasts.We find a disproportionately large number of stock repurchases among firms that would have missed analysts’ forecasts without the repurchase.Relevance watch 2

Norwegian Air converted $1B worth of debt to shares. To qualify for the government support, the airline had to deleverage by converting the bonds to shares.Relevance watch 3
The airline’s financial moves reflected its dire cash crunch.The airline that brought Europe’s low-cost business model to the transatlantic market, flying more people to New York than any other non-U.S. carrier, has now grounded 95% of its fleet and furloughed or laid off most staff.Relevance watch 3

Revenue RecognitionQUESTION 1-1
Layaway Goodies should recognise revenue when the good is delivered (i.e., its benefits and risks are transferred to the buyer) and match expenses then.

Forbes: Stock Buybacks Made Corporations Vulnerable (April 24, 2020)Relevance watch 1

Instead of innovation, companies whose business models were undergoing a high degree of uncertainty and change repurchase stock.Since Q1 2009, S&P 500 companies have spent, cumulatively, $5.4 trillion on stock buybacks.Perhaps no greater example is the U.S. airlines, an industry that has collectively spent 96% of free cash flow on buybacks over the last decade, leaving virtually no cash cushion to prepare for a down cycle.Relevance watch 1
Despite what many CEOs consistently say on earnings calls—that buybacks “return value” to shareholders—share repurchases in actuality put a company and its shareholders in a much riskier position.“Instead of using capital to invest in the future (i.e. electric cars), car companies like GM buy back company stock.”So do stock buybacks increase risk for long-term shareholders?Relevance watch 1

Reuters: Norwegian Air to sell new shares at close to 80% discount (May 5, 2020)Relevance watch 3

Norwegian Air converted $1B worth of debt to shares.  The new shares valued at 1 crown, compared to 4.8 crown (the trading price right before the conversion).The airline’s objective was to obtain Norwegian Government’s line of credit of $300M.  To qualify for the government support, the airline had to deleverage by converting the bonds to shares.Relevance watch 3
The airline’s financial moves reflected its dire cash crunch.The airline that brought Europe’s low-cost business model to the transatlantic market, flying more people to New York than any other non-U.S. carrier, has now grounded 95% of its fleet and furloughed or laid off most staff.Relevance watch 3
